The British Virgin Islands authorities have introduced a number of precautionary measures in response to the coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic.
With effect from Sunday 22 March 2020 at 11:59 p.m. for a period of fourteen (14) days, in the first instance, all airports and seaports in the Virgin Islands be closed to inbound passengers (whether nationals or non-nationals) until Monday 6 April 2020 at 11:59 p.m., except as pre-authorised. The restriction does not apply to freight, cargo or courier craft or vessels. International crew members on incoming vessels will be required to remain within the port facility and comply with all Public Health measures in effect. Further information on BVI travel advice can be found at the website of the Government of the Virgin Islands.
Further information on risks to travellers, avoidance measures, symptoms and how to self-quarantine is available on the BVI Ministry of Health and Social Development website.
With effect from Thursday 19th March, all schools, pre-schools and day-care centres will be closed for an initial period of 14 days. Additionally, with effect from Monday 23 March until Friday 17 April 2020 all non-essential gatherings of 20 persons or more will be prohibited This includes all social gatherings including faith-based, sporting, cultural, recreational and commercial activities. For the same period, all businesses and services and all recreational facilities will be closed 8:00 p.m. until 6:00 a.m. daily.
A decision has been made to postpone the BVI Spring Regatta and the Virgin Gorda Easter Festival.
British nationals wishing to leave the British Virgin Islands should make arrangements to do so as soon as possible. See Return to the UK for more information.
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
